    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i also want to dive into the idea of \"property rights\" applied to digital spaces—like the idea that any state-mandated rule on a platform interferes with the natural autonomy of the users and the infrastructure itself. can you expand on how libertarian thinkers use property rights to argue against regulation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Libertarian thinkers, particularly those influenced by the Austrian School, argue that the internet is a vast, decentralized network of property rights, with users and platforms as the primary proprietors. The concept of \"digital property rights\" asserts that online infrastructure, data, and content are the natural extensions of physical property rights, and that government regulation infringes upon these rights. This perspective is rooted in the idea that the internet's decentralized nature renders traditional notions of territorial sovereignty and regulatory authority obsolete.",
      "source": "target",
